idCitation.resTitle: Rio Buildings clipped to SpaceNet Challenge AOI 2.

dataIdInfo.idPurp: Buildings in Rio de Janeiro clipped to SpaceNet Challenge AOI 2
dataIdInfo.idAbs:
UNCLASSIFIED

Overall, the city’s buildings are aging and suffer from poor economic upkeep during the tough economic times of the past decades. The city also has trouble enforcing building codes. On January 25, 2012, this struggle showed when three prominent buildings collapsed and 17 people died in downtown Rio, adjacent to the Municipal Theater where Obama addressed Brazilian leaders in 2011. Enforcing construction codes and bringing buildings up to par continue to be leading concerns for the government as the Olympic Games approach. As a whole, the World Bank’s Doing Business Report ranks the country 169 out of 189 for dealing with construction permits.

The Tallest building in Rio is the Rio Sul Center, a shopping mall and business condominium built in 1982 that stands at 535 ft. tall with 48 floors.

The Brazilian Institute of Architects launched two competitions to prepare the city for the Olympics and create a legacy for the city. The Rio Olympic Port Competition aims at the revitalization and redevelopment of the port city of Rio de Janeiro to include the construction of the media and referees villages, a five-star hotel, a convention center, and business center for the Games, and this project coincides with the project of the Marvelous Port Recovery Center of Rio de Janeiro. The Rio Olympic Park Masterplan Competition garnered 59 teams from 18 countries. The winning team, AECOM UK, bid for a prestigious project on approximately 120 hectares of land in the district of Barra de Tijuca to be based on sport, recreation, sustainability, and ecology. Environmental concerns are a top priority for new buildings and construction projects are a top priority for Mayor Eduardo Paes.

Collection

The feature class was generated utilizing data from DigitalGlobe Worldview-2 pan-sharpened ortho-rectified satellite imagery. Building outline shapes contain spatial detail reflective of the visible characteristics of the building footprints as seen from the source imagery.

The data included herein have not been derived from a registered survey and should be considered approximate unless otherwise defined. While rigorous steps have been taken to ensure the quality of each dataset, DigitalGlobe is not responsible for the accuracy and completeness of data compiled from outside sources.

Metadata information was collected from various private organizations and news media articles.
